1
00:00:21,550 --> 00:00:25,115
BASED ON A TRUE STORY

2
00:00:42,919 --> 00:00:45,517
A FILM BY
DENNIS GANSEL

3
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:14,730
THE WAVE

4
00:02:07,192 --> 00:02:08,277
Good morning.

5
00:02:14,699 --> 00:02:15,827
Good morning.

6
00:02:22,152 --> 00:02:25,070
Making sure the kids
don't smoke in the yard, huh?

7
00:02:27,919 --> 00:02:29,943
Hi, honey.

8
00:02:29,943 --> 00:02:31,628
Hey, my rocker!

9
00:02:31,628 --> 00:02:34,181
You know we teachers are lazy, 
don't spoil our image.

10
00:02:34,181 --> 00:02:37,260
Just doing some copying.
You seen Mrs Kohlhage?

11
00:02:37,260 --> 00:02:38,458
No, why?

12
00:02:38,458 --> 00:02:40,280
She was looking for you.

13
00:02:40,280 --> 00:02:42,366
Better see what she wants.

14
00:02:44,394 --> 00:02:47,441
Autocracy? I thought there was a clear deal 
that I'll do the Anarchy class.

15
00:02:47,882 --> 00:02:52,521
Mr Wieland showed me his outline for the whole week. 
It's well thought-out. 

16
00:02:52,743 --> 00:02:56,684
- I'd have done mine this weekend.
- A bit late.

17
00:02:56,684 --> 00:02:59,135
Wieland? 
Wieland doesn't have a clue about it.

18
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:03,499
I studied in Berlin.
I`ve lived five years in the last house in Kreuzberg.

19
00:03:03,927 --> 00:03:06,668
May 1st demonstrations, always there.
I'm an expert.

20
00:03:07,314 --> 00:03:10,144
If it's that important,
ask Mr Wieland to trade.

21
00:03:12,972 --> 00:03:15,054
Couldn't you...?

22
00:03:15,648 --> 00:03:17,732
Work it out between yourselves.

23
00:03:22,421 --> 00:03:24,505
Mr Wieland?

24
00:03:24,505 --> 00:03:26,691
Mr Wenger.

25
00:03:26,691 --> 00:03:29,973
- About the project subjects...
- Yes, and?

26
00:03:29,973 --> 00:03:33,695
Could you trade with me?
I'm doing autocracy.

27
00:03:33,695 --> 00:03:35,779
<i>Alea iacta est.</i>

28
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:39,924
The die is cast.

29
00:03:40,320 --> 00:03:42,705
You know I wanted to do anarchy.

30
00:03:42,705 --> 00:03:44,925
A bit too much!

31
00:03:44,925 --> 00:03:49,838
Project week is for showing the students
the virtues of democracy.

32
00:03:51,088 --> 00:03:53,196
How to make Molotov cocktails...

33
00:03:53,481 --> 00:03:55,830
maybe only in chemistry class.

34
00:03:56,292 --> 00:03:57,876
Have a nice day.

35
00:04:00,926 --> 00:04:04,096
I loved you. You betrayed me.

36
00:04:04,096 --> 00:04:07,068
But I haven't forgotten
my dream of life, love and trust,

37
00:04:07,638 --> 00:04:10,159
the dream that once was real.

38
00:04:10,406 --> 00:04:15,453
I will build it with my fortune
by destroying you.

39
00:04:16,028 --> 00:04:19,851
Hey, thanks for the daisies, babe.

40
00:04:20,662 --> 00:04:23,580
They'll look great
when I'm lying in the box.

41
00:04:23,580 --> 00:04:24,818
He's making a fool of himself.

42
00:04:24,818 --> 00:04:28,420
Know what I'm sayin', babe?

43
00:04:32,128 --> 00:04:34,684
"I'll take you to Capri in your coffin..."

44
00:04:34,684 --> 00:04:38,393
- He's saying it wrong.
- It's what I want to say.

45
00:04:38,393 --> 00:04:41,287
Ferdi, can't we do it right through for once?

46
00:04:41,501 --> 00:04:44,521
You're the one who stopped.
First stage rule:

47
00:04:44,521 --> 00:04:46,030
The show must go on!

48
00:04:46,030 --> 00:04:50,357
Dennis, aren't we applying 
the play's criticism of capitalism to today?

49
00:04:50,357 --> 00:04:53,273
That's why I'm updating the dialogue.

50
00:04:53,273 --> 00:04:55,491
Okay, but don't make a joke out of it.

51
00:04:55,491 --> 00:04:56,918
He can't assert himself.

52
00:04:56,918 --> 00:04:59,607
Yeah, we're doing Drrenmatt,
not <i>Quatsch Comedy-Club.</i>

53
00:05:01,087 --> 00:05:04,942
I thank you for the wreaths,
chrysanthemums and roses...

54
00:05:04,942 --> 00:05:06,739
Noble.

55
00:05:06,739 --> 00:05:10,647
That sounds like shit.
No way I'm saying that.

56
00:05:10,647 --> 00:05:12,027
Forget it.

57
00:05:12,027 --> 00:05:16,038
If Ferdi doesn't stick to his lines,
I can't do it.

58
00:05:20,393 --> 00:05:22,783
I've had enough. Are you coming?

59
00:05:23,383 --> 00:05:27,053
It's a pity they're not taking it seriously.

60
00:05:27,053 --> 00:05:29,321
It's no use if everybody does what they want.

61
00:05:30,677 --> 00:05:32,760
Coming to the game today?

62
00:05:33,282 --> 00:05:35,365
Lisa and I have to study for Spanish.

63
00:05:35,365 --> 00:05:37,555
Not all afternoon?

64
00:05:37,555 --> 00:05:39,741
What did you sign up for?

65
00:05:40,007 --> 00:05:41,411
Sign up?

66
00:05:41,411 --> 00:05:43,178
Project week.

67
00:05:43,178 --> 00:05:45,691
- Are the lists up already?
- Sure.

68
00:05:45,691 --> 00:05:48,902
- I was thinking of autocracy.
- Me too.

69
00:05:49,535 --> 00:05:50,910
Gotta go.

70
00:05:50,910 --> 00:05:53,670
- Will you sign me up?
- For what?

71
00:05:53,670 --> 00:05:57,624
- Whatever you take.
- Okay.

72
00:06:01,985 --> 00:06:04,068
See you later.

73
00:06:24,126 --> 00:06:27,551
Pull yourself together, okay?
I wanna see some real play.

74
00:06:27,551 --> 00:06:30,271
Watch your defence and counter man to man. 
Got it?

75
00:06:30,596 --> 00:06:33,560
Eight minutes left. We can do it!

76
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:37,982
Marco, that goes for you too.
Play as a team.

77
00:06:46,683 --> 00:06:48,767
Let's go!

78
00:06:59,836 --> 00:07:01,920
Mogli, move the ball up!

79
00:07:05,437 --> 00:07:07,522
Nice, Marco!

80
00:07:09,864 --> 00:07:11,963
Marco!
Sinan's wide open!

81
00:07:11,963 --> 00:07:14,047
- Marco!
- Go for it! 

82
00:07:17,887 --> 00:07:19,705
What are you doing, damn it?

83
00:07:19,705 --> 00:07:21,789
Sinan was wide open!

84
00:07:21,789 --> 00:07:24,054
Don't you want to score?

85
00:08:50,488 --> 00:08:52,573
Martin, you tell me...

86
00:08:52,781 --> 00:08:56,092
What are we supposed 
to rebel against nowadays?

87
00:08:56,770 --> 00:08:58,657
Nothing means anything anymore.

88
00:08:58,657 --> 00:09:02,233
We all just want to have fun.

89
00:09:02,543 --> 00:09:07,194
What our generation lacks
is a common goal to unite us.

90
00:09:07,194 --> 00:09:09,733
That'd just be the <i>Zeitgeist.</i>
Look around.

91
00:09:10,234 --> 00:09:15,515
The most Googled name on the Internet
is Paris Fucking Hilton!

92
00:09:15,515 --> 00:09:18,223
- No shit.
- No shit.

93
00:09:19,083 --> 00:09:21,986
Hey, let it out,
it`ll be better.

94
00:09:31,062 --> 00:09:33,147
Stolte.

95
00:09:35,879 --> 00:09:37,962
You got the dope today?

96
00:09:37,962 --> 00:09:40,212
Sure I do.

97
00:09:44,168 --> 00:09:46,737
- This is the real thing?
- Sure is.

98
00:09:46,737 --> 00:09:48,823
A buddy brought it from Holland.

99
00:09:50,110 --> 00:09:52,579
Are you nuts,
carrying that much dope?

100
00:09:53,647 --> 00:09:55,731
Cops have to catch me first.

101
00:09:58,127 --> 00:10:00,212
What do you want for it?

102
00:10:02,562 --> 00:10:05,070
- Nothing.
- What?

103
00:10:05,070 --> 00:10:08,964
It's free for you.
You're my homeys.

104
00:10:15,031 --> 00:10:17,715
MONDAY

105
00:10:38,472 --> 00:10:40,014
Baby.

106
00:10:40,014 --> 00:10:42,100
The water's great, 
probably 16 degrees.

107
00:10:43,556 --> 00:10:45,639
Don't you want to go for a swim?

108
00:10:45,639 --> 00:10:47,580
It'd do you good.

109
00:10:47,580 --> 00:10:49,445
Maybe later.

110
00:10:49,445 --> 00:10:51,184
How's your shoulder?

111
00:10:51,184 --> 00:10:52,304
It's okay now.

112
00:10:52,304 --> 00:10:54,389
Don't overdo it.

113
00:10:54,830 --> 00:10:56,912
Yeah, sure.

114
00:10:57,955 --> 00:10:59,285
Coffee?

115
00:10:59,285 --> 00:11:01,371
Sure, thanks.

116
00:11:06,794 --> 00:11:08,876
Morning.

117
00:11:09,811 --> 00:11:10,980
What's up?

118
00:11:10,980 --> 00:11:13,066
- Okay, Rainer?
- Yeah.

119
00:11:13,754 --> 00:11:15,838
- Morning, Rainer.
- Sinan.

120
00:11:18,042 --> 00:11:22,336
I have to say I'm surprised so many of you
are interested in autocracy.

121
00:11:22,336 --> 00:11:24,501
I'd have chosen anarchy.

122
00:11:24,501 --> 00:11:27,818
- Lame Wieland?
- Your words, not mine!

123
00:11:30,701 --> 00:11:31,421
So...

124
00:11:44,423 --> 00:11:46,506
Autocracy. What does it mean?

125
00:11:48,765 --> 00:11:50,849
Come on,
you signed up for this topic,

126
00:11:51,068 --> 00:11:53,184
you must have certain expectations.

127
00:11:53,592 --> 00:11:55,674
No hassles, I hope.

128
00:11:57,319 --> 00:12:00,233
Jens, what do we mean
by autocratic government?

129
00:12:00,757 --> 00:12:03,882
- Stuff like monarchy, I guess.
- Not necessarily.

130
00:12:03,882 --> 00:12:05,862
Ferdi, what can you think of?

131
00:12:05,862 --> 00:12:07,947
Autos that are crass!

132
00:12:09,271 --> 00:12:11,356
That was pretty lame.

133
00:12:11,343 --> 00:12:13,030
Lisa, don't let me down.

134
00:12:13,030 --> 00:12:16,959
- Dictatorship, maybe? 
- That's part of it. Karo?

135
00:12:16,959 --> 00:12:21,860
I think autocracy is when an individual 
or a group rules the masses.

136
00:12:21,860 --> 00:12:23,470
Right.

137
00:12:23,470 --> 00:12:27,009
Autocracy comes from the Greek
and means self-rule.

138
00:12:27,009 --> 00:12:31,249
From <i>auto</i>, "self",
and <i>kratia</i>, "power", "rule"...

139
00:12:31,249 --> 00:12:35,279
In an autocracy, the ruler 
or a group of rulers

140
00:12:35,279 --> 00:12:38,165
have unlimited power
to change the law as they like.

141
00:12:38,472 --> 00:12:40,556
Can you think of any examples?

142
00:12:42,325 --> 00:12:44,587
Come on, a dictatorship! 

143
00:12:44,587 --> 00:12:48,071
- The Third Reich.
- Not again.

144
00:12:48,071 --> 00:12:51,857
I didn't pick the topic, but we have 
to get through this week together.

145
00:12:52,644 --> 00:12:54,728
I printed out some things for you.

146
00:12:54,728 --> 00:12:56,346
All that stuff again?

147
00:12:56,346 --> 00:12:58,321
It's an important topic.

148
00:12:58,321 --> 00:13:00,994
The Nazis sucked.
All right, we get it!

149
00:13:00,994 --> 00:13:03,009
Right, shit nazis!

150
00:13:03,009 --> 00:13:05,831
- And it's never gonna happen here again.
- What about Neo-Nazis?

151
00:13:05,831 --> 00:13:08,687
We can't feel guilty forever,
for something we didn`t do.

152
00:13:08,897 --> 00:13:13,226
We're not talking about guilt.
It's a historical responsibility.

153
00:13:13,226 --> 00:13:15,476
Me a Turk, man!

154
00:13:15,773 --> 00:13:18,641
- Okay, we all know!
- What do we know?

155
00:13:18,641 --> 00:13:20,340
Except for some idiot East Germans...

156
00:13:20,340 --> 00:13:22,742
Hey, I'm from the East!

157
00:13:22,951 --> 00:13:24,732
You know what I mean, skinheads.

158
00:13:24,732 --> 00:13:26,996
- Rainer, can't we do something else?
- Like? 

159
00:13:26,996 --> 00:13:28,663
The Bush administration.

160
00:13:29,035 --> 00:13:31,119
Wait, this is interesting.

161
00:13:31,119 --> 00:13:34,514
You think another dictatorship
would be impossible in Germany?

162
00:13:34,514 --> 00:13:36,657
We're way beyond that.

163
00:13:38,277 --> 00:13:40,360
Marco, what do you think?

164
00:13:42,550 --> 00:13:44,633
Beats me.

165
00:13:54,696 --> 00:13:56,781
We'll take a ten-minute break.

166
00:14:18,598 --> 00:14:20,683
What's the deal?

167
00:14:21,104 --> 00:14:23,795
I changed the seating.
Now there's more room for everyone.

168
00:14:23,813 --> 00:14:25,598
Bring your table behind.

169
00:14:34,217 --> 00:14:37,194
Fortunately, we can do whatever we want 
during project week.

170
00:14:38,497 --> 00:14:42,665
I propose we loosen things up a bit.
Any objections?

171
00:14:44,004 --> 00:14:46,087
Very good.

172
00:14:46,740 --> 00:14:49,904
What are the requirements
for an autocratic system?

173
00:14:50,479 --> 00:14:52,198
Dennis?

174
00:14:52,198 --> 00:14:54,855
- An ideology.
- Good. What else?

175
00:14:54,855 --> 00:14:57,462
- Control.
- Surveillance.

176
00:14:57,462 --> 00:14:59,547
You're getting ahead of yourselves.

177
00:14:59,547 --> 00:15:01,528
Unhappiness.

178
00:15:01,528 --> 00:15:03,560
Interesting.

179
00:15:03,560 --> 00:15:07,779
What does every dictatorship need?
We already mentioned it.

180
00:15:07,779 --> 00:15:09,337
A <i>Fhrer</i>, man!

181
00:15:09,337 --> 00:15:10,170
A <i>Fhrer?</i>

182
00:15:10,170 --> 00:15:12,409
A word with lots of baggage.

183
00:15:12,409 --> 00:15:14,932
But every dictatorship has a central figure.

184
00:15:15,798 --> 00:15:18,541
Let's go through this.
Who would that be here?

185
00:15:18,981 --> 00:15:20,277
- You, the teacher.
- Me?  

186
00:15:20,277 --> 00:15:22,107
Who else?

187
00:15:22,107 --> 00:15:24,687
One of you, for a change.

188
00:15:29,133 --> 00:15:31,217
I'll be the leader.

189
00:15:31,636 --> 00:15:34,853
No way! Rainer, you do it.

190
00:15:34,853 --> 00:15:35,895
Let's vote.

191
00:15:35,895 --> 00:15:38,664
Who wants me as your project leader?

192
00:15:39,202 --> 00:15:41,286
- What is this?
- Play along.

193
00:15:42,158 --> 00:15:44,241
Who's against? Any nays?

194
00:15:46,012 --> 00:15:48,096
Abstentions?

195
00:15:48,928 --> 00:15:51,845
- Good.
- <i>Heil</i> Rainer!

196
00:15:51,845 --> 00:15:54,116
Of course, a leader deserves respect.

197
00:15:55,468 --> 00:15:58,884
So you'll address me as Mr Wenger
for project week.

198
00:15:58,884 --> 00:16:02,370
- Mr Wenger...
- Is he a megalomaniac now?

199
00:16:02,683 --> 00:16:04,667
We just voted on it, didn't we?

200
00:16:04,667 --> 00:16:08,204
- East German commie!
- Get with the programme!

201
00:16:08,204 --> 00:16:10,289
Don't tell me what to do, bitch!

202
00:16:11,247 --> 00:16:13,099
Watch your mouth, scumbag!

203
00:16:13,099 --> 00:16:16,338
Quiet!
Clear off your desks.

204
00:16:17,061 --> 00:16:19,698
From now on,
no one talks without permission.

205
00:16:19,925 --> 00:16:23,416
- Yes, sir!
- Did I give you permission?

206
00:16:23,936 --> 00:16:24,780
No.

207
00:16:24,780 --> 00:16:27,373
If you want to speak,
you'll stand up first.

208
00:16:27,595 --> 00:16:30,819
- Isn't that going a bit far?
- Mona?

209
00:16:34,009 --> 00:16:36,621
Isn't that going a bit far,
Mr Wenger?

210
00:16:36,621 --> 00:16:38,522
- Feel anything?
- What?

211
00:16:38,522 --> 00:16:40,608
Standing up gets your circulation going.

212
00:16:40,608 --> 00:16:42,674
It's blood pressure.

213
00:16:42,674 --> 00:16:45,666
If you stand up, you wake up
and your concentration improves.

214
00:16:47,458 --> 00:16:49,543
You can sit down again.

215
00:16:51,130 --> 00:16:55,617
Marco. You're tired from training,
but try sitting up straight.

216
00:16:55,617 --> 00:17:00,843
Straighten your spine,
place your feet parallel and breathe deeply.

217
00:17:02,178 --> 00:17:04,263
Feel the difference?

218
00:17:05,532 --> 00:17:06,552
Marco.

219
00:17:09,174 --> 00:17:11,256
Yes, Mr Wenger.
It's better.

220
00:17:11,550 --> 00:17:13,977
That's right,
you can breathe better.

221
00:17:15,302 --> 00:17:17,176
Let's all do the same.

222
00:17:17,176 --> 00:17:19,938
Everybody get up.

223
00:17:19,938 --> 00:17:21,674
- Come on!
- What is this?

224
00:17:21,674 --> 00:17:23,759
Breathe deeply.

225
00:17:24,085 --> 00:17:25,955
Up you get.

226
00:17:25,955 --> 00:17:28,040
Breathe in...

227
00:17:28,948 --> 00:17:31,033
and out.

228
00:17:32,618 --> 00:17:34,700
- What's with you?
- No way!

229
00:17:35,744 --> 00:17:37,826
Then leave, please.

230
00:17:38,036 --> 00:17:41,927
No one's forcing you to stay.
Attendance is voluntary.

231
00:17:44,164 --> 00:17:46,311
- Rainer, be cool.
- Mr Wenger.

232
00:17:46,946 --> 00:17:50,944
Kevin, it's very simple.
Either play along or leave.

233
00:17:53,315 --> 00:17:55,399
Well?

234
00:17:56,560 --> 00:17:58,691
This is weirding me out.

235
00:18:01,038 --> 00:18:03,121
Come on, Sinan.
Bomber.

236
00:18:12,761 --> 00:18:14,845
Later daze!

237
00:18:16,897 --> 00:18:18,981
You can sit down again.

238
00:18:20,545 --> 00:18:22,629
What else is important for a dictatorship?

239
00:18:26,589 --> 00:18:30,067
- Discipline, Mr Wenger.
- Very good, Tim.

240
00:18:30,067 --> 00:18:32,152
Power through discipline.

241
00:18:35,271 --> 00:18:37,356
Let's go shoot some pool.

242
00:18:41,171 --> 00:18:43,255
I've got a better idea.

243
00:18:43,763 --> 00:18:47,560
Man, what's that?
What happened to your M-class?

244
00:18:47,560 --> 00:18:49,931
It's my mom's, a wedding anniversary gift 
from my father.

245
00:18:50,889 --> 00:18:53,209
V-8, 250 bhp, 150 mph.

246
00:18:53,500 --> 00:18:56,506
Wanna take this baby
for a spin on the highway?

247
00:18:59,235 --> 00:19:01,320
What's with you?

248
00:19:01,646 --> 00:19:05,074
- I'm not coming.
- What do you mean?

249
00:19:05,074 --> 00:19:06,549
I'm going back.

250
00:19:06,549 --> 00:19:08,239
Have you completely lost your mind 
or what?

251
00:19:08,239 --> 00:19:10,536
I've already failed twice.

252
00:19:10,536 --> 00:19:12,671
You know what happens
if I don't graduate?

253
00:19:14,654 --> 00:19:16,739
You're no honours student either.

254
00:19:19,182 --> 00:19:21,266
I'm glad you changed your mind.

255
00:19:21,266 --> 00:19:23,461
Have a seat in the back.

256
00:19:24,094 --> 00:19:26,176
Thanks... Mr Wenger.

257
00:19:27,637 --> 00:19:32,640
We were discussing which social conditions
favour a dictatorship.

258
00:19:39,099 --> 00:19:41,184
Lisa?

259
00:19:45,352 --> 00:19:49,436
- Which social conditions are necessary?
- Could you speak up, please? 

260
00:19:49,837 --> 00:19:52,845
Well, like, if there's injustice....

261
00:19:54,193 --> 00:19:57,684
and, like, people don't know...
I mean, no jobs and stuff.

262
00:19:58,204 --> 00:20:00,288
Hey, Ferdi! 
What's the big idea?

263
00:20:00,576 --> 00:20:02,925
Lisa, please just sit down again.

264
00:20:04,013 --> 00:20:05,968
Take a deep breath.

265
00:20:05,968 --> 00:20:08,726
Think what you're going to say.
Keep your answer short.

266
00:20:09,347 --> 00:20:11,223
I know you can do it.

267
00:20:11,223 --> 00:20:13,307
Try it again, okay?

268
00:20:14,458 --> 00:20:17,079
High unemployment and social injustice.

269
00:20:17,079 --> 00:20:20,763
Excellent. 
High unemployment and social injustice,

270
00:20:21,338 --> 00:20:23,590
certainly would favour a dictatorship.

271
00:20:25,394 --> 00:20:26,942
Tim?

272
00:20:26,942 --> 00:20:28,835
High inflation, Mr Wenger.

273
00:20:28,835 --> 00:20:30,097
Good. Inflation.

274
00:20:30,097 --> 00:20:32,788
- Political disillusionment.
- Very good, Karo.

275
00:20:32,788 --> 00:20:34,037
Nationalism.

276
00:20:34,037 --> 00:20:38,104
We saw it during the World Cup,
there were German flags everywhere.

277
00:20:38,439 --> 00:20:40,767
- But that was great!
- I thought it was revolting.

278
00:20:41,502 --> 00:20:43,587
That's what rocked about the World Cup!

279
00:20:44,485 --> 00:20:49,125
If Germans can't be proud of their country, 
like anyone else,

280
00:20:49,125 --> 00:20:51,211
it just leads to the reverse,

281
00:20:51,211 --> 00:20:53,429
to hatred of everybody else.

282
00:20:53,429 --> 00:20:59,487
I think Mona means extreme nationalism.
Can we agree on that?

283
00:21:04,017 --> 00:21:07,017
That was awesome today.
Thank you. 

284
00:21:08,110 --> 00:21:09,813
Sr. Wenger?

285
00:21:09,813 --> 00:21:11,897
After class call me Rainer again.

286
00:21:11,897 --> 00:21:14,109
I really enjoyed it today.

287
00:21:14,109 --> 00:21:16,236
Keep up your contributions.

288
00:21:16,236 --> 00:21:18,321
Yes sir, Mr Wenger!

289
00:21:31,100 --> 00:21:32,490
Watch it!

290
00:21:32,490 --> 00:21:34,376
Why don't you watch it?

291
00:21:34,376 --> 00:21:36,139
Be nice to your sister.

292
00:21:36,139 --> 00:21:37,963
Just gimme a light!

293
00:21:37,963 --> 00:21:40,590
- You shouldn't smoke.
- My dad says I can.

294
00:21:40,590 --> 00:21:42,019
I've got a light.

295
00:21:42,019 --> 00:21:45,165
Torsten just said it's up to you.

296
00:21:45,165 --> 00:21:47,249
None of your business, anyway.

297
00:21:49,792 --> 00:21:51,874
Ignore the little weirdo.

298
00:21:52,103 --> 00:21:54,062
- Retard!
- You're the retard!

299
00:21:54,062 --> 00:21:56,148
Don't you have a home of your own?

300
00:22:03,956 --> 00:22:05,518
Hi, hon.

301
00:22:05,518 --> 00:22:07,091
Hi, sweetie.

302
00:22:07,091 --> 00:22:08,642
You thirsty, too?

303
00:22:21,603 --> 00:22:23,688
Aren't you going to ask me how it went?

304
00:22:26,256 --> 00:22:27,918
How did it go?

305
00:22:27,918 --> 00:22:30,035
It was totally fascinating.

306
00:22:30,424 --> 00:22:32,293
Mr Wenger taught us how to sit properly.

307
00:22:32,293 --> 00:22:35,055
Upright, with your spine straight.

308
00:22:35,628 --> 00:22:39,663
You know when you stand up quickly
and your vision goes all blurry?

309
00:22:40,177 --> 00:22:42,248
That's because your pulse is low.

310
00:22:42,248 --> 00:22:44,233
More roast?

311
00:22:44,233 --> 00:22:48,443
Now we have to stand up to speak.
It's good for your circulation,

312
00:22:48,443 --> 00:22:50,844
and our answers must always be 
short and concise.

313
00:22:51,047 --> 00:22:53,315
Good. Why don't you, then?

314
00:22:56,262 --> 00:23:00,764
There was this bizarre energy,
everybody was caught up in it.

315
00:23:00,969 --> 00:23:03,524
"Bizarre" is right.

316
00:23:03,818 --> 00:23:05,440
What's that supposed to mean?

317
00:23:05,440 --> 00:23:07,525
"Power through discipline"...

318
00:23:07,525 --> 00:23:12,387
Karo, honey, 
that's not how we raised you.

319
00:23:14,267 --> 00:23:16,352
Maybe you should have.
Leon could use a bit of discipline.

320
00:23:16,892 --> 00:23:18,976
Your brother needs to learn his own limits.

321
00:23:19,283 --> 00:23:21,367
It doesn't work for everyone.

322
00:23:21,879 --> 00:23:22,836
Why?

323
00:23:22,836 --> 00:23:24,920
Kevin, for example, 
I had to kick him out of class.

324
00:23:24,920 --> 00:23:27,109
I'll kick your ass!

325
00:23:28,620 --> 00:23:30,854
Get off it! Rainer's cool.

326
00:23:31,056 --> 00:23:34,812
- You traitor!
- I'd have kicked you out too.

327
00:23:34,812 --> 00:23:37,332
Besides, Rainer didn't kick you out,
Mr Wenger did.

328
00:23:38,991 --> 00:23:42,887
He never liked me 'cause I'm not 
in his faggy water-polo team.

329
00:23:43,558 --> 00:23:45,643
What do you guys do there?

330
00:23:45,643 --> 00:23:48,601
We practise hard.
I don't know why we're losing.

331
00:23:49,359 --> 00:23:55,173
We have to beat Ernst-Barlach-Gesamtschule,
or we'll lose our league standing.

332
00:23:55,899 --> 00:23:57,763
Come by sometime.

333
00:23:57,763 --> 00:23:59,359
When's your next game?

334
00:23:59,359 --> 00:24:01,444
Marco, let's go to my room.

335
00:24:01,794 --> 00:24:03,710
We're watching the race.

336
00:24:03,710 --> 00:24:05,795
We can watch it in my room.

337
00:24:05,795 --> 00:24:08,127
We have our project assignment.

338
00:24:08,668 --> 00:24:11,966
- What assignment?
- Are you coming?

339
00:24:13,473 --> 00:24:15,340
Sorry, Torsten.

340
00:24:15,340 --> 00:24:18,263
You go study for your project assignment.

341
00:24:20,233 --> 00:24:22,317
Hey, my little honeybee.

342
00:24:23,509 --> 00:24:25,947
What say we do our own 
"project assignment"?

343
00:24:26,480 --> 00:24:29,313
I hear role-playing
can be pretty stimulating. 

344
00:24:35,397 --> 00:24:37,482
I thought we were going
to do something else.

345
00:24:40,814 --> 00:24:42,608
Here, check this out.

346
00:24:42,608 --> 00:24:43,884
Here's where we'll go.

347
00:24:43,884 --> 00:24:48,156
The hippest part of Barcelona,
only seven stations to the soccer stadium.

348
00:24:49,931 --> 00:24:51,967
Isn't it a bit far?

349
00:24:51,967 --> 00:24:54,051
Seven stations?

350
00:24:55,257 --> 00:24:56,762
Barcelona.

351
00:24:56,762 --> 00:25:00,297
It's beautiful, right on the sea.
An artist's city.

352
00:25:03,224 --> 00:25:05,306
Wouldn't your family miss you?

353
00:25:05,306 --> 00:25:07,541
They get on my nerves.

354
00:25:07,848 --> 00:25:09,672
Torsten and Bine are cool.

355
00:25:09,672 --> 00:25:11,757
Sometimes they're too cool for me.

356
00:25:13,583 --> 00:25:15,668
Stop whining.

357
00:25:16,670 --> 00:25:18,754
Come here.

358
00:25:19,588 --> 00:25:21,672
I'm not in the mood.

359
00:25:21,672 --> 00:25:24,031
You're not moving tomorrow.
What's the hurry?

360
00:25:24,284 --> 00:25:26,368
I have to sign up soon.

361
00:25:28,061 --> 00:25:30,145
Then sign up.

362
00:25:31,087 --> 00:25:33,171
Come on, don't go yet.

363
00:25:33,637 --> 00:25:35,722
I've got practice.

364
00:26:19,968 --> 00:26:22,481
Wait, not here. Come on.

365
00:26:33,872 --> 00:26:37,241
Man, what kind of shit is this? 
What is that?

366
00:26:43,028 --> 00:26:45,093
Damn it! 
You can`t do everything you want in here.

367
00:26:43,028 --> 00:26:47,177
When youÂ´ll finally understand that?

368
00:26:47,699 --> 00:26:49,534
- Listen, man...
- Leave me alone.

369
00:26:49,534 --> 00:26:53,314
Let's play together. 
Everyone will expect you to hog the ball.

370
00:26:53,314 --> 00:26:56,400
I'll swim into the clear on the left
and pass back to you, okay?

371
00:27:03,395 --> 00:27:05,479
Get out! Slo, you play.

372
00:27:22,776 --> 00:27:24,860
Nice, Marco!
That's better.

373
00:27:25,508 --> 00:27:27,593
Great move, with class!

374
00:27:27,593 --> 00:27:29,763
Finally!

375
00:27:31,531 --> 00:27:33,615
Hi, sweetie, I'm home.

376
00:27:38,084 --> 00:27:40,168
What's going on?

377
00:27:40,802 --> 00:27:42,884
I just want to print something.

378
00:27:43,463 --> 00:27:46,779
Kiki and Alex are really a pain in the ass,
a real couple of teachers.

379
00:27:47,796 --> 00:27:49,878
Are we like them?

380
00:27:53,113 --> 00:27:54,545
What's all this for?

381
00:27:54,545 --> 00:27:56,692
Just a few ideas I want to try out tomorrow.

382
00:27:58,529 --> 00:28:00,611
I have a few ideas too!

383
00:28:06,634 --> 00:28:08,611
Only if you wear a nurse costume.

384
00:28:08,611 --> 00:28:10,095
We'll see.

385
00:28:10,095 --> 00:28:12,179
How about an injection?

386
00:28:12,787 --> 00:28:14,871
I've got an injection that's all ready to go!

387
00:28:15,913 --> 00:28:17,040
- Really? 
- Yes.

388
00:28:17,040 --> 00:28:19,125
Let's see it, then.

389
00:28:21,951 --> 00:28:24,310
TUESDAY

390
00:28:24,880 --> 00:28:26,074
Here he comes. 

391
00:28:32,189 --> 00:28:35,134
- Morning.
- Good morning, Mr Wenger.

392
00:28:39,532 --> 00:28:41,614
I have a feeling you don't
take me seriously, do you?

393
00:28:41,614 --> 00:28:43,132
No, of course we do.

394
00:28:43,132 --> 00:28:45,217
Everybody stand up, please.

395
00:28:45,217 --> 00:28:47,476
Now do as I do.

396
00:28:48,621 --> 00:28:52,592
These are a few warm-up exercises
to loosen up your muscles.

397
00:28:53,544 --> 00:28:55,628
Especially the legs.

398
00:28:56,232 --> 00:28:58,316
And now in unison.

399
00:28:58,813 --> 00:29:01,643
Left, right...

400
00:29:06,786 --> 00:29:08,730
What is this for?

401
00:29:08,730 --> 00:29:10,813
I want to show you something.

402
00:29:11,820 --> 00:29:13,418
Good.

403
00:29:13,418 --> 00:29:14,772
You feel it?

404
00:29:14,772 --> 00:29:17,277
We're becoming a single unit.

405
00:29:18,339 --> 00:29:20,423
That's the power of unity.

406
00:29:24,329 --> 00:29:27,905
- How long do we keep this up?
- Until we're in step.

407
00:29:27,905 --> 00:29:29,885
You know that from dancing, Mona.

408
00:29:29,885 --> 00:29:32,330
Left, right...

409
00:29:33,251 --> 00:29:36,149
A rhythm like this
can cause bridges to collapse.

410
00:29:36,861 --> 00:29:39,433
- Kaschi, you're out of step.
- Chill, man!

411
00:29:40,293 --> 00:29:42,377
I think we get it, Mr Wenger.

412
00:29:42,377 --> 00:29:44,587
I don`t think so.

413
00:29:44,587 --> 00:29:47,749
- This exercise has another purpose.
- What's that?

414
00:29:47,749 --> 00:29:49,913
Wieland's anarchy class is below us.

415
00:29:51,562 --> 00:29:55,417
I want the plaster to fall off the ceiling 
onto our "enemy" heads!

416
00:29:56,572 --> 00:29:58,656
Excellent!

417
00:30:09,217 --> 00:30:11,301
Have they gone crazy?

418
00:30:14,888 --> 00:30:16,974
Unity is power.

419
00:30:17,968 --> 00:30:20,577
You want to know 
why I rearranged the seating?

420
00:30:21,452 --> 00:30:23,536
To break up your usual cliques.

421
00:30:24,476 --> 00:30:27,627
You all have your friends and groups.
That's important.

422
00:30:28,332 --> 00:30:30,306
You can't get through life all by yourself,

423
00:30:30,306 --> 00:30:32,655
but together, we are much, much stronger.

424
00:30:33,434 --> 00:30:35,980
The new seating has a method to it.

425
00:30:35,980 --> 00:30:38,122
Do you know what it is?

426
00:30:38,384 --> 00:30:40,467
Anyone?

427
00:30:40,467 --> 00:30:43,277
Karo, why are you sitting next to Jens 
and not Marco?

428
00:30:44,379 --> 00:30:46,249
Because Marco and I distract each other?

429
00:30:46,249 --> 00:30:48,334
Oh, do you?

430
00:30:49,585 --> 00:30:54,518
Wieland down there wants to foster his students
by making them lone warriors.

431
00:30:54,518 --> 00:30:58,054
You know what I mean.
No one letting the other copy.

432
00:30:58,343 --> 00:31:00,635
I say that leads to social Darwinism.

433
00:31:00,635 --> 00:31:03,442
I'm convinced if we pull together,

434
00:31:03,442 --> 00:31:05,568
we'll be much stronger.

435
00:31:05,568 --> 00:31:07,686
So we can copy from each other?

436
00:31:07,943 --> 00:31:10,090
If it means better grades, yes.

437
00:31:11,489 --> 00:31:13,574
That's why I've checked your grades,

438
00:31:13,574 --> 00:31:15,834
and seated the good grades 
next to the bad.

439
00:31:16,569 --> 00:31:18,054
I want you to help each other.

440
00:31:18,054 --> 00:31:20,033
That's total nonsense!

441
00:31:20,033 --> 00:31:22,118
- Mona?
- I don't believe it. 

442
00:31:22,118 --> 00:31:24,375
Please stand up.

443
00:31:26,877 --> 00:31:28,961
You wouldn't embarrass us like this.

444
00:31:29,380 --> 00:31:33,068
All the poor students are lined up 
like ducks in a row.

445
00:31:33,471 --> 00:31:35,479
I never said anything about poor students,

446
00:31:35,479 --> 00:31:37,564
just poor grades.

447
00:31:38,657 --> 00:31:40,532
There are no poor students.

448
00:31:40,532 --> 00:31:44,077
For example, you're good in my class,
but you struggle in math.

449
00:31:44,248 --> 00:31:46,741
Lisa, however, is a math whiz.

450
00:31:47,929 --> 00:31:49,910
You could help each other.

451
00:31:49,910 --> 00:31:51,994
There's another advantage.

452
00:31:52,729 --> 00:31:55,431
The whole class would do better,

453
00:31:55,431 --> 00:31:57,875
at least better 
than the anarchists downstairs.

454
00:32:00,132 --> 00:32:02,217
I know it's unorthodox...

455
00:32:03,465 --> 00:32:05,592
but why not try something new?

456
00:32:08,769 --> 00:32:10,872
Hey, Domi. 
We were pretty loud, huh?

457
00:32:12,008 --> 00:32:14,527
How's it going with Wieland,
our Bavarian?

458
00:32:14,527 --> 00:32:19,081
I thought anarchy would be interesting,
but he just blows.

459
00:32:19,081 --> 00:32:21,218
He is like a sleeping pill.

460
00:32:21,218 --> 00:32:23,702
If you guys hadn't raised hell,
I would've dozed off.

461
00:32:24,401 --> 00:32:25,713
What was that?

462
00:32:25,713 --> 00:32:27,993
A little calisthenics to wake them up.

463
00:32:27,993 --> 00:32:29,522
Calisthenics?

464
00:32:29,522 --> 00:32:31,560
I thought the building was going to collapse.

465
00:32:31,560 --> 00:32:35,379
You disrupt my classes. 
My students are outraged, and justly so.

466
00:32:35,692 --> 00:32:36,735
Can I help you kids?

467
00:32:36,735 --> 00:32:40,793
We wanted to ask if we can switch
to the autocracy class.

468
00:32:41,217 --> 00:32:43,301
Right away, if possible.

469
00:32:49,087 --> 00:32:51,117
We were talking about group unity.

470
00:32:51,117 --> 00:32:53,200
What are the signs of group unity?

471
00:32:55,756 --> 00:32:57,527
Team spirit, Mr Wenger.

472
00:32:57,527 --> 00:32:59,695
Good, but I meant visual signs.

473
00:32:59,995 --> 00:33:01,015
Lisa? 

474
00:33:02,179 --> 00:33:05,765
- Dress, Mr Wenger?
- Exactly, a common way of dressing.

475
00:33:06,708 --> 00:33:09,274
One could also say by uniforms.

476
00:33:09,523 --> 00:33:11,286
Uniforms suck.

477
00:33:11,286 --> 00:33:13,370
Dominik?

478
00:33:15,038 --> 00:33:17,819
I mean, uniforms are totally fascistic.

479
00:33:17,819 --> 00:33:20,026
It might be so,
but not necessarily military uniforms.

480
00:33:20,547 --> 00:33:24,337
There are all kinds of uniforms everywhere:
McDonald's, stewardesses, meter maids...

481
00:33:24,826 --> 00:33:26,910
even business suits are a dress code.

482
00:33:27,449 --> 00:33:29,968
Your outfit is a kind of uniform too.

483
00:33:29,968 --> 00:33:32,119
It indicates your social group.

484
00:33:34,201 --> 00:33:36,285
Lisa?

485
00:33:37,535 --> 00:33:39,619
Uniforms can serve another purpose.

486
00:33:39,619 --> 00:33:42,386
They eliminate social differences.

487
00:33:42,603 --> 00:33:45,175
Yes, they do, 
but also they eliminate individuality.

488
00:33:46,043 --> 00:33:48,127
Mona, please stand up.

489
00:33:49,622 --> 00:33:51,704
Lisa, explain it more accurately.

490
00:33:52,017 --> 00:33:56,472
Well, I mean, we all stress out
every morning over what to wear.

491
00:33:57,231 --> 00:33:59,889
If we all wore a uniform,
we wouldn't have to.

492
00:34:00,588 --> 00:34:01,290
Karo? 

493
00:34:01,290 --> 00:34:05,058
I've heard that in Hamburg they're talking
about reintroducing school uniforms.

494
00:34:05,058 --> 00:34:07,246
Does that make sense?

495
00:34:07,973 --> 00:34:08,693
Sinan? 

496
00:34:10,174 --> 00:34:13,858
Sure, but they'd have to be cheap enough 
for everyone to afford.

497
00:34:16,504 --> 00:34:18,589
Marco, why don't you tell everybody?

498
00:34:18,900 --> 00:34:20,999
I was saying... 

499
00:34:25,157 --> 00:34:31,051
Stephon Marbury of New York Knicks, 
made a basketball shoe that cost only $14.99.

500
00:34:31,714 --> 00:34:33,799
The "Starbury One".

501
00:34:35,381 --> 00:34:38,079
He was a ghetto kid and wanted a shoe
kids could afford,

502
00:34:38,079 --> 00:34:40,674
instead of expensive Nike Airs.

503
00:34:40,882 --> 00:34:43,745
A good example.
How can he market them so cheaply?

504
00:34:44,040 --> 00:34:46,561
Because they're made
in Chinese slave factories.

505
00:34:47,747 --> 00:34:49,830
No, they just do 
without expensive ad campaigns.

506
00:34:50,491 --> 00:34:53,565
Nike spends hundreds of millions on ads.

507
00:34:54,140 --> 00:34:56,357
David Beckham got millions from Adidas.

508
00:34:58,177 --> 00:35:04,115
What say we adopt a school uniform
for the duration of project week?

509
00:35:04,960 --> 00:35:06,341
Like what?

510
00:35:06,341 --> 00:35:09,120
Maybe a pair of jeans, a white shirt.
Everyone has that.

511
00:35:10,052 --> 00:35:12,899
- I don't have a white shirt.
- Then buy one.

512
00:35:12,899 --> 00:35:15,381
I'm not spending money for that.

513
00:35:15,381 --> 00:35:17,182
Come on, how much can it cost?

